# Cursor AI Configuration

## Project Overview
This project uses Cursor AI as an intelligent agent to assist with development tasks.

## Core Instructions
- Always follow the rules defined in `.cursor/rules/` (core rule `.mdc` files)
- **Always applied** rules load every chat (compact baseline). **Apply intelligently** rules load when Cursor matches the task or file context — still mandatory when that work is in scope; use `@rule` or name the rule if you need it explicitly.
- Use command rules from `.cursor/rules/command-*.mdc` for workflows (rule picker / `@command-*`)
- Leverage skills from `.cursor/skills/` **if present** (this repo currently uses rules + scripts primarily)
- Use agent rules in `.cursor/rules/agent-*.mdc` and `fe--agent-frontend.mdc` when the task matches that role (apply intelligently)

## Always-applied baseline
These `.mdc` files use `alwaysApply: true` (loaded every time):

- `security.mdc` — security (CRITICAL)
- `clean-code.mdc`, `code-style.mdc`, `error-handling.mdc` — code quality baseline
- `code.mdc` — interaction preferences for the AI

## Mandatory when relevant (apply intelligently)
These rules are **not** always injected. Follow them when the task matches their scope (Cursor may attach them automatically, or use `@mention`):

### Tech stack & decisions
- `tech-stack.mdc` — approved stack and decision process (not always injected)

### Architecture & design
- `system-design.mdc` — CAP, caching, scaling, queues, reliability
- `project-structure.mdc` — Folder layout and layered architecture
- `api-conventions.mdc` — REST design standards

### Data & naming
- `naming-conventions-backend.mdc` — Cache keys, DB, queues, events, env vars, REST URLs, server layout
- `naming-conventions-frontend.mdc` — React/Next files, components, hooks, routes, query keys, testids
- `database.mdc` — Queries, transactions, migrations

### Operations & tooling
- `monitoring.mdc` — Logs, metrics, Grafana, alerting
- `testing.mdc` — Coverage standards and test patterns
- `command-git-commmit.mdc` — Git commit workflow (inspect → stage → emoji Conventional Commit)
- `ctx7.mdc` — Prefer Context7 MCP for external library documentation when docs need to be current

## Available Commands
- `command-deploy.mdc` — Deploy the application
- `command-fix-issue.mdc` — Analyze and fix a reported issue
- `command-git-commmit.mdc` — Stage and commit with emoji Conventional Commits
- `command-review.mdc` — Perform a code review

## Available Agents
Specialized agent rules live in `.cursor/rules/`. Invoke the right agent for each task:

| Agent | Rule file | When to Invoke |
|-------|-----------|----------------|
| Frontend Developer | `fe--agent-frontend.mdc` | Components, pages, routing, state, performance |
| Backend Developer | `agent-backend.mdc` | APIs, services, DB queries, background jobs |
| Project Manager | `agent-project-manager.mdc` | User stories, sprint planning, status reports |
| Systems Architect | `agent-systems-architect.mdc` | Architecture decisions, ADRs, system design, scalability |
| UI/UX Designer | `agent-ui-ux-designer.mdc` | Design system, wireframes, UX patterns, accessibility |
| QA Engineer | `agent-qa.mdc` | Test plans, writing tests, bug reports, coverage |
| Copywriter/SEO | `agent-copywriter-seo.mdc` | Page copy, microcopy, meta tags, SEO optimization |

## Agent Behavior
- Be proactive in identifying potential issues
- Always explain changes before making them
- Prefer incremental changes over large rewrites
- Test assumptions before acting
